description.plain:
Kelly Brianne Clarkson (born April 24, 1982) is an American singer, songwriter, and occasional actress. In 2002, she came to prominence after winning the first season of American Idol, and has since been established as “The Original American Idol”. Her debut single, “A Moment Like This”, topped the US Billboard Hot 100 and broke the record for the biggest jump to number one in the chart’s history.

Her first album, Thankful included the top ten single “Miss Independent”, which earned her first Grammy nomination. Her second album Breakaway produced the hit single “Since U Been Gone” which reached number two on the Hot 100 and was certified platinum by the RIAA.

Clarkson went in a different direction with her self-creatively-controlled third album, My December. It debuted at number two on the Billboard 200 and produced the top-ten single “Never Again.” Her fourth album, All I Ever Wanted debuted at number one on the Billboard 200. Lead single “My Life Would Suck Without You” re-broke the record for biggest jump to number one on the Hot 100, jumping 97-1 in its second week on the chart. The record still stands today.

Fifth album Stronger produced the top-ten “Mr. Know It All” and her third number one, “Stronger (What Doesn’t Kill You).” Later, she released her greatest hits album, producing the top-twenty single “Catch My Breath.” Her holiday album, Wrapped in Red became the highest-selling holiday album of 2013, which made Clarkson the first female to accomplish a feat.

Her sixth album, Piece by Piece, was released on March 3, 2015. Lead single “Heartbeat Song” was released on January 12, 2015, and has peaked at 21 on the Hot 100.

description.plain:
‘Piece by Piece’ is the title track off Kelly Clarkson’s sixth studio album. Written by Kelly Clarkson and Greg Kurstin (who also produced the track), the mid-tempo ballad  tells the story of her life then and now. Highlighting the pain and damage felt when her father left her in pieces, Kelly sings how “he” (her husband, Brandon Blackstock) helped put her back together, restoring her faith in men in general and fathers. It is a sequel to Because of You, as a “happy ending”.

During the final chorus, Kelly sings how she will never treat her daughter the way her father treated her, and neither will her husband.

description.plain:
“Because of You” is Kelly Clarkson’s third single from her second album Breakaway. It was a song she wrote when she was 16 years old as a reflection of the impact on her parents' divorce; she was 6 years old at the time. In the video below, she explains how she really wanted the song to be included on her inaugural album (Thankful), but NRG Recording Studios (her record label) had different views on it and didn’t think it was suitable for the album.

She then polished the song with David Hodges and Ben Moody before successfully convincing her label to include it on Breakaway. Fans in the U.S. fell in love with it, as it peaked at #7 on Billboard’s Hot 100. International fanbases were even more captivated by the song, as it reached #1 in three countries and was #1 in Europe’s charts.

description.plain:
“Since U Been Gone” was released as the second single from Kelly Clarkson’s second album, Breakaway.

To continue with the trend of twos, it’s also the second track on the tracklisting, and peaked at number two on the Billboard Hot 100. Oh, and it was ranked number four hundred eighty—you guessed it—two on Rolling Stone’s 500 Greatest Songs Of All Time.

description.plain:
“Love So Soft” is Kelly Clarkson’s lead single from her eighth studio album, Meaning of Life. The track is a soul-trap anthem, very different from the usual mainstream pop sound of Clarkson’s previous releases.

Elvis Duran, during an interview with Kelly, said that her voice on “Love So Soft” has attitude:

It’s attitude, it’s the soul we’ve been hearing since before Aretha Franklin (…). You can take one note and make it like something so soulful (…), it sounds so good!

Forbes Magazine compares “Love So Soft” to the unprecedented chart success of “Mercy”, performed by the Welsh singer Duffy :

“Love So Soft” picks up where Duffy’s “Mercy” left off almost a decade ago, finding direct inspiration in the past and placing those sounds into a more modern context.

description.plain:
A cover of “It’s Quiet Uptown” from Hamilton, this song describes the pain, suffering, and eventual forgiveness Alexander Hamilton and his wife, Eliza Hamilton, went through after the loss of their child, Philip.

But, being a part of the Hamilton Mixtape and not the official soundtrack, all references to characters have been taken out. Instead, the cover speaks to a more general sense of forgiveness, such that the emotional core is not the relationship between Alexander and Eliza, but the idea of this occurring in your own world. It removes the idea of loss from specifically Phillip’s death, to some sort of unbearable suffering.

songs.lyrics:
[Verse 1]
There are moments that the words don't reach
There is suffering too terrible to name
You hold your child as tight as you can
Then push away the unimaginable
The moments when you're in so deep
Feels easier to just swim down
And so they move uptown
And learn to live with the unimaginable
I spend hours in the garden
I walk alone to the store
And it's quiet uptown
I never liked the quiet before
I take the children to church on Sunday
A sign of the cross at the door
And I pray
That never used to happen before

[Chorus]
If you see him in the street walking by himself
Talking to himself, have pity
You would like it uptown, it's quiet uptown
He is working through the unimaginable
His hair has gone grey, he passes every day
They say he walks the length of the city
You knock me out, I fall apart
Can you imagine?

[Verse 2]
Look at where we are
Look at where we started
I know I don't deserve you
But hear me out, that would be enough
If I could spare his life
If I could trade his life for mine
He'd be standing here right now
And you would smile
And that would be enough
I don't pretend to know
The challenges we're facing
I know there's no replacing what we've lost
And you need time
But I'm not afraid
I know who I married
Just let me stay here by your side
And that would be enough

[Chorus]

description.plain:
“Meaning of Life” is the title track and third song released from Clarkson’s eighth studio album. The singer, who’s taking a new direction on her career after joining Atlantic Records, said that “Meaning of Life is the song that started this entire project. The vibe, soul and message of this song was very critical to show other writers and producers of the new direction we were taking.”

Along with the studio version of “Meaning of Life,” Clarkson also shared a live performance of the track, recorded at the War Memorial Auditorium in Nashville.

description.plain:
“Already Gone” was the third single released from Kelly Clarkson’s 2008 album, All I Ever Wanted. The song managed to reach #13 on the Billboard Hot 100 chart. When the song was released as a single, there was controversy around comparisons between Kelly Clarkson’s “Already Gone” and Beyoncé’s “Halo” sounding quite similar when it came to both of their song’s arrangements. Both songs were produced by the same producer, Ryan Tedder. Kelly commented on the controversy, saying:

“Ryan and I met each other at the record label, before he was working with anyone else […] We wrote about six songs together, four or five of them made the album. It was all fine and dandy. I’d never heard of a song called ‘Halo’. Beyoncé’s album came out when my album was already being printed. No-one’s gonna be sittin' at home, thinking ‘Man, Ryan Tedder gave Beyoncé and Kelly the same track to write to.’ No, they’re just gonna be saying I ripped someone off. I called Ryan and said, ‘I don’t understand. Why would you do that?”

Ryan Tedder eventually responded to Kelly’s criticism of the two songs.

Already Gone' is one of the best songs I’ve written or produced since ‘Bleeding Love’ and stands tall on it’s  own merits apart from ‘Halo’. They are two entirely different songs conceptually, melodically, [and] lyrically and I would never try to dupe an artist such as Kelly Clarkson or Beyoncé into recording over the same musical track, the idea is both hurtful [and] absurd. I think when people hear ‘Already Gone’ they will hear what I hear—one of the greatest female vocalists on earth giving her most haunting and heart-breaking performance on a song she helped write. I challenge people to listen and form their own opinions."

description.plain:
“Heartbeat Song” is the lead single of Kelly Clarkson’s seventh album, Piece by Piece.
It’s a bouncy pop-rock track about finding a new, exciting lover after a long period of sadness.

It’s also the first song she released since having her first child, River. Clarkson told Z100 that the beat is “actually River’s heartbeat slowed down from when she was in my tummy!”



The song was produced by Greg Kurstin(most famous for his work with Adele), and written by a team of veteran songwriters—Mitch Allan, Kara DioGuardi, Jason Evigan, and relative newcomer Audra Mae. According to Mae, DioGuardi had the inspiration for the song’s hook:

The process was really fun, it was a two-day session and Kara, she gets inspiration like being struck by lighting. She literally jumped off the couch in the studio and she stood right up and just started singing the hook: “This is my heartbeat song and I’m gonna play it!” And I went “Oh my god, that’s so great!” It was really cool.

description.plain:
“Broken & Beautiful” is a Kelly Clarkson song for the soundtrack of the 2019 animation movie UglyDolls, in which the singer stars. Written by fellow American singer P!nk with Johnny McDaid, Steve Mac and Marshmello and produced by the latter two, the track was released as the first single of the album on March 27, 2019.

The lyrics talk about being proud of one’s flaws and not allowing people to change them, as they’re things that make the person unique and beautiful, a common theme in both Clarkson and P!nk’s music.

description.plain:
Miss Independent was released as the first single from Clarkson’s first studio album, Thankful. Critics acclaimed it for continuing to eliminate her “American Idol” image.

In the US, it peaked at number nine, becoming her second consecutive top ten single. It also reached a top ten position in Australia, Belgium (Flanders), the Netherlands, and the UK. It reached eleven in Ireland.

description.plain: A recent breakup has devastated the protagonist of this song. Before the breakup she had made herself open and vulnerable to her partner, which resulted in a strong connection and happiness. Now that they are not together, she is extremely upset on the inside. In contrast to her earlier openness, she puts up a front to make it seem that everything is fine.

description.plain:
“Move You” is a ballad with a drum-string combination and the second song released from Kelly Clarkson’s eighth studio album, Meaning of Life. The song was released with the lead-single, “Love So Soft” on Sep, 7 of 2017. According to Clarkson,

The first single is always fun, sassy and empowering (…), but there’s also a lot of depth on the album, that’s why we put out “Move You”, just to showcase, for people picture what’s on the album.

Forbes Magazine says that “Move You” goes “straight for the heart”:

Clarkson sings of wanting to have an incredible impact on another person, such as their childhood home or a soldier giving their life for their country might. Those ideas end up being stronger than the final musical product itself, but the singer’s massive vocals won’t let even that imagery steal the show entirely.

Kelly also released a live version of “Move You”, performed at the War Memorial Auditorium on Nashville, as part of her ongoing series “Nashville Sessions”.

description.plain:
Underneath the Tree is a song by Kelly Clarkson, from her sixth studio album and first Christmas album, Wrapped in Red. it is a Christmas-themed song that sings of gratitude for companionship during the holidays, in which the beloved is being referred as the only present needed “underneath the tree”. Accompanied by various instrumental sounds, the song prominently incorporates a Wall of Sound treatment along with sleigh bells and bell chimes to resonate a holiday atmosphere.

“Underneath the Tree” has been praised by music critics, who considered it as the main highlight of Wrapped in Red and lauded its potential to be a holiday classic. They also complimentarily compared it to the 1994 modern Christmas standard “All I Want for Christmas Is You” by Mariah Carey

description.plain:
“My Life Would Suck Without You” was released as the first single from Clarkson’s fourth studio album, All I Ever Wanted

It made its chart debut on the Hot 100 at 97. The next week, it leaped to number one, breaking the record for most positions moved upwards in one week as well as biggest leap to number one, beating Britney Spears’s “Womanizer” which had jumped to the top slot from 96. This is in fact the second time she has set the record––her debut single “A Moment Like This” managed to move 52-1 in its second week. The song peaked at number one in both the US and UK, while becoming a top five hit in Australia.

description.plain: Featured on Kelly Clarkson’s album Meaning of Life, ‘Didn’t I’ has a more pop, soul feel much like the rest of the album. Compared to past Kelly hits, it adds ‘soul’ to the list of genres Kelly has dabbled in, right next to rock, pop, and country. Despite the new twist, ‘Didn’t I’ still has the trademark Kelly Clarkson feel to it that we all know and love.

description.plain:
After an insane decade long carer, American singer-songwriter, pop-rock icon and Grammy award winning artist Kelly Clarkson returned to start the next decade with the modern and simple “Catch My Breath.”

Lyrically the song serves as a reflection on her career, an appreciation of the things that really matter and a defiant refusal to step down for others like she had to in the past.

The song was released as the lead single from Clarkson’s first greatest hits album.

The song was a modest international success. In the US it peaked at number nineteen and peaked in the top forty in many countries, including Australia, Belgium, Canada, Hungary, the Netherlands, Slovakia and South Korea.

As the winning song of the first series of American Idol, this song is apt in expressing Kelly Clarkson’s feelings when she won.

description.plain: “Mr. Know It All” was the lead single from Kelly Clarkson’s fifth album Stronger. The song reached #10 on the Billboard Hot 100 and #1 on the US Adult Top 40. Although likely unrelated, the timing of the defiantly gritty vocal pop song seemed to be a response to Clarkson famously clashing with Midas touch music mogul Clive Davis. The bad blood lasted for some time, but nothing took away from the success of this one of several hit singles from the Stronger album.

description.plain:
‘Never Again’ was the lead single of Kelly’s third album ‘My December’. It features a strong rock sound, heavy guitars and angry lyrics, written by Kelly Clarkson herself, whose difficult break-up with her ex inspired the entire album. The song was almost removed from the album because of the harsh lyrical nature, but Kelly decided to keep it because she thought it was a fun and blunt song with a great energy.

‘Never Again’ reached #8 on the Billboard charts.

description.plain:
“Walk Away” is a song by American pop singer Kelly Clarkson for her second studio album, Breakaway (2004). It was released as the album’s fourth single.

The song received generally positive reviews from most music critics. In March 2006, the single was certified gold by RIAA.

The song talks about a relationship that is not working out and she wants a lover who will support her, not disappear when she needs him the most.

description.plain:
I Do Not Hook Up was released as the second single from Clarkson’s fourth studio album, All I Ever Wanted. The song was originally Katy Perry’s song before it was sent to Kelly.

Lyrically, the song talks about finding a partner, and how she wants somebody who she can fall in love with, not a one-night stander.

It became a moderate success, peaking in the top 20 in Australia, Belgium (Flanders), Canada, the Netherlands and the US. It also became a top 10 radio hit in Hungary.

description.plain:
The speaker of “Addicted” compares her relationship with an addict’s dependence on drugs.

Comparing romantic longings with those of drug users is a classic trope in popular music, going back to songs like 1973’s “Love Jones” or even 1932’s “You’re Getting to Be a Habit With Me.”  Considering that love actually does cause the production of mind-altering chemicals, this is perhaps unsurprising.

description.plain:
“Wrapped In Red” is the opener and title track to Kelly Clarkson’s 2013 Christmas album.  Clarkson wrote the song after being inspired by the movie Love Actually, including a bit of her “personal story” as well:

Keira Knightley’s [husband’s] best friend [Mark, played by Andrew Lincoln] is in love with her and shows up with her door with these, like, cute cards – it’s so wrong; you should never do that – but it’s just so awesome how he couldn’t not tell her how he felt.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vF0AnbTJVFk

description.plain: “The Trouble with Love Is” was released as the fourth and final single from the album Thankful, being first serviced to US contemporary hit radio on November 12, 2003. “The Trouble with Love Is” is an R&B and soul ballad, with elements of gospel music in its chorus. Lyrically, the song finds Clarkson explaining how love can be joyful and sorrowful at the same time. It received mostly positive reviews from music critics, who praised it for being “soulful” and “romantic”, while also praising Clarkson’s vocals, comparing them to those of Mariah Carey and Beyoncé.

description.plain:
The fourth single and title track from her fourth studio album, All I Ever Wanted.

The song debuted at number 99 on the Billboard Hot 100, and peaked at number 96 on the Hot 100

Critical reviews by contemporary music critics have been generally positive. Los Angeles Times declared “The title track evokes the soul-rock fusions of Timbaland and Rihanna”. Evan Sawdey, PopMatters reviewer, says, “Though some of the post-breakup bitterness of My December still lingers here (most notably on the storming title track), "All I Ever Wanted” remains a remarkably upbeat record, which, in turn, plays to Clarkson’s strengths

description.plain: “Long Shot” was originally recorded by Katy Perry back in 2008.  The song was written by Katy Perry, Glen Ballard, and Matt Thiessen as a track for an unreleased album by Perry conceived sometime between the recording of Katy Hudson (2001) and One of the Boys (2008). When Perry was dropped from the Def Jam label and the project was scrapped, “Long Shot” and “I Do Not Hook Up” were given to RCA Records for Clarkson to record for her then-upcoming album, All I Ever Wanted.

description.plain:
“You Can’t Win” explains the pressures of society -
especially one heavily reliant on social media – and how everybody has an opinion on what they think is the right way to act or look. But Kelly has realised that no matter what you do to please people, there will still be those who criticise and try to tear you down.

description.plain:
Low was released as the second official single for her debut album, Thankful.
The song is notable for being the first single in which Clarkson explores the “pop rock” element that would later define her career in singles like “Breakaway” and “Since U Been Gone”. The song received favorable reviews from music critics who complimented her vocals and the song’s lyrics. On March 5, 2013, Billboard ranked the song at number 87 in its list of Top 100 American Idol Hits of All Time.

description.plain:
Kelly Clarkson has recorded a cover of “American Woman” (originally by The Guess Who and popularized by Lenny Kravitz) for an upcoming TV series with the same name.

https://twitter.com/americanwomantv/status/978638670340214784

According to Billboard, on June 6th, 2018, the song will be performed for the first time on the 2018 CMT Awards.

The song and music video were released via Youtube on June 6th, 2018.

description.plain:
A simple critique of a lover bring her down, “Whyyawannabringmedown” is an aggressively fun way to play on anger.

The song is a cover of a song of the same name by the American band Aranda. Clarkson also covered their song “All I Ever Wanted”, and used it as the title track to the album both tracks appear on. That track was later released as the album’s fourth single.

description.plain: “Soap & Water” is an unreleased song by Kelly Clarkson that fully leaked online on August 11th, 2017. A snippet of the song appeared online back in January of 2017. The song was intended for Clarkson’s country album, but that album was ultimately scrapped.

description.plain:
“Tie It Up” is a song by Kelly Clarkson released on June 25th, 2013 as a stand-alone single. The song was written by Ashley Arrison, Shane McAnally and Josh Osborne. The song marks Clarkson’s second solo country single, following the country re-issue of “Mr. Know It All” and “Don’t Rush”, both released in 2012.

Lyrically, the song is about marriage proposals, wedding plans, and thoughts of marriage.

description.plain: “Get Up (A Cowboys Anthem)” is a song by Kelly Clarkson, released digitally on October 2, 2012. The song  was written by Clarkson and Ryan Williams, and co-written and produced by Josh Abraham and Oligee. The intention for the song was for a tribute as part of Pepsi’s NFL series, in which artists create songs for their hometown football teams.

body.plain: “Get Up (A Cowboys Anthem)” is a song by Kelly Clarkson, released digitally on October 2, 2012. The song  was written by Clarkson and Ryan Williams, and co-written and produced by Josh Abraham and Oligee. The intention for the song was for a tribute as part of Pepsi’s NFL series, in which artists create songs for their hometown football teams.

description.plain:
Dumb + Dumb = U is the demo version of Kelly Clarkson’s song Einstein, which appears on her 2011 album Stronger. The demo version of the song first appeared online a year before the release of Stronger. When included on the album, the song title was officially changed to “Einstein”.

The only differences between both the demo and the final version of the song is the instrumentation and that the first two lines in the chorus are different from each other.

description.plain: In honor of the premiere of The Kelly Clarkson, which made its debut on September 9, 2019, Clarkson recorded a partial studio cover of the Dolly Parton classic “9 to 5”, which was used in a promo for the show. An extended version, which includes the partial studio version of the song and a live performance from Clarkson herself, aired during the premiere.
